@soiferj After fusion the Relay program is split into several parts like
```
%x = fn(...) {
  dense
  relu
}
```
Each part is passed to `tvm.build_module` independently. So the thing is to find exactly which part is broken

Yes, I did rebase.

I think I know what's going wrong in unification and have a couple of ideas as to how to address it. The problem indeed stems from introducing constraints from multiple functions at once.

Suppose we have the following two functions and simultaneously add them to the module:
```
def @f1[a](x) -> list[a] {
  Cons(x, Nil)
}

def @main() {
  f1(S(Z()))
}
```

`x` in the first one has no type annotation so `f1` will be introduced into the module with type `fun[a](?t1) -> l(a)` ([here](https://github.com/dmlc/tvm/pull/2648/files#diff-d25dae80d06c671132c543c097e695beR874)) where `?t1` is an incomplete type. When the inference procedure reaches `main`, the call to `f1` will treat `f1`'s type as `fun[a](?t1) -> l(a)` and `?t1` will be unified with the type of `S(Z())`, which is `nat`. But when the procedure checks `f1`, the type of `Cons(x, Nil)` will be unified with the annotated return type `list[a]`, so `?t1` will be unified with `a`. That is how we end up trying to unify `a` and `nat`. When adding functions one at a time, we resolve between each function and so never end up in this situation.

I think my mistake is not making the initial types general enough [here](https://github.com/dmlc/tvm/pull/2648/files#diff-d25dae80d06c671132c543c097e695beR874). I think the let polymorphism changes should make it easier to give these a more general type and have things work out. I will experiment with a few possible ways of getting around the issue noted here.
